<LP>
   PHILIP MORRIS AGREED to acquire 80% of Swiss coffee and
chocolate maker Jacobs Suchard for $3.8 billion. Suchard's
trove of brands, including Toblerone chocolate, will
significantly strengthen the U.S. firm's European presence
before trade barriers fall in 1992 and will help lessen the
company's dependence on tobacco sales in the U.S.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Orders for durable goods leaped 3.9% in May, suggesting to
some that the manufacturing sector is stabilizing. But other
parts of the economy may be softening; personal income rose
only 0.3% in the month, while personal spending was flat.
                                                                                                       

   Machine tool orders dropped 29% in May from a high April
rate but were above a year earlier.
   ---
   The Dow Jones industrials tumbled 44.55 points Friday to
2857.18, the average's lowest level since Memorial Day. The
sell-off in stocks pushed bond prices modestly higher.
   ---
   USX has held "exploratory" talks with foreign investors
about the possible sale of some of its steel operations.
USX's chairman played down the likelihood of such a move but
said the firm's future is in energy.
   ---
   First Brands' controlling shareholders are seeking to sell
all or part of the consumer-products firm. Its stock jumped
on the annnouncement.
   ---
   Zinc and lead prices are expected to rise sharply if new
labor contracts aren't reached this week at Canada's two
largest producers, Cominco Ltd. and Noranda Inc.'s Brunswick
unit.
   ---
   NBC may overhaul its daytime schedule, perhaps expanding
the "Today" show to three hours.
   ---
   The EPA is expected to propose today that second-hand
smoke be declared a human carcinogen, which could encourage
more firms to adopt total workplace bans on smoking.
   ---
   The prison term for former Drexel trading assistant Lisa
Jones was reduced to 10 months from 18 months.
   ---
   Trump gained the consent of three Japanese banks for a
bailout loan. The proposal's fate now appears to rest with
two European banks.
   ---
   Circle K named Cincinnati lawyer Bart Brown to be
chairman, succeeding Karl Eller, who quit in May.
   ---
   Bank of New England named a new head of its main unit as
part of a continuing shuffling of management.
   ---
   Northrop and McDonnell unveiled their version of the Air
Force's next-generation fighter. But the jet is emerging just
as lawmakers question how much such a warplane is needed.
